{"questionId":"2738573","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows part of the curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>cos</mi><msqrt><mi>x</mi></msqrt></math> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/63b408474491c64c96f1cc8d8f5289869b4fd591.png\"></p>\n<p>The curve intersects the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-axis at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> ….</p>\n<p>The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>th <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-intercept of the curve, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></math>, is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>∈</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Write down a similar expression for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A</strong><strong>1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2738573","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ2.12b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Write down a similar expression for xn+1.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.5—Integration introduction, areas between curve and x axis","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.10—Indefinite integration, reverse chain, by substitution","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.11—Definite integrals, areas under curve onto x-axis and areas between curves","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.16—Integration by substitution, parts and repeated parts","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.5—Unit circle definitions of sin, cos, tan. Exact trig ratios, ambiguous case of sine rule","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.4—Key features of graphs, intersections using technology","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.2—Arithmetic sequences and series"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}